  "summary": "<a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/25/a-clown-fought-a-robot-in-1897-and-we-can-finally-watch-it.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"A clown fought a robot in 1897, and we can finally watch it\"><img alt=\"Georges Méliès&#039; Gugusse et l&#039;Automate (1897)\" class=\"webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image\" height=\"906\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/robot.jpg?fit=1200%2C906&amp;quality=60&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto; margin-bottom: 5px;\" width=\"1200\" /></a><p>A 45-second film from 1897 — the earliest known cinematic depiction of a robot-like figure — has been rediscovered after being lost for over a century. A nitrate print of Georges Méliès' <em>Gugusse et l'Automate</em> turned up in Michigan and was <a href=\"https://blogs.loc.gov/loc/2026/02/lost-19th-century-film-by-melies-discovered-at-the-library/\">restored by the Library of Congress</a>, which means you can now watch it for the first time in generations. &#8212; <a class=\"read-more\"",
